<paragraph blockId="5.[192,1441,197,413]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[240,378,197,221]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Genitalia.</emphasis>
Aedeagus as is 
<figureCitation box="[569,640,197,221]" captionStart="Figure 6-8" captionStartId="4.[193,276,1867,1889]" captionTargetBox="[203,1433,201,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-39@4.[203,861,201,1843]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 6-8. Parahyliota balli Thomas, new species. Male genitalia. 6) Aedeagus. 7) Tegmen. 8) Claspers, composed of abdominal segments VIII and IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5405019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5405019/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
; parameres highly reduced (
<figureCitation box="[986,1056,197,221]" captionStart="Figure 6-8" captionStartId="4.[193,276,1867,1889]" captionTargetBox="[203,1433,201,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-39@4.[203,861,201,1843]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 6-8. Parahyliota balli Thomas, new species. Male genitalia. 6) Aedeagus. 7) Tegmen. 8) Claspers, composed of abdominal segments VIII and IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5405019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5405019/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
), abdominal segments VIII and IX forming claspers as in 
<figureCitation box="[505,577,229,253]" captionStart="Figure 6-8" captionStartId="4.[193,276,1867,1889]" captionTargetBox="[203,1433,201,1843]" captionTargetId="figure-39@4.[203,861,201,1843]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figure 6-8. Parahyliota balli Thomas, new species. Male genitalia. 6) Aedeagus. 7) Tegmen. 8) Claspers, composed of abdominal segments VIII and IX." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5405019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5405019/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[192,1441,197,413]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[240,349,261,285]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Female.</emphasis>
<materialsCitation collectionCode="USNM" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="allotype">
<typeStatus box="[354,456,261,285]" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Allotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation box="[470,562,261,285]" captionStart="Figure 4-5" captionStartId="3.[193,277,1901,1923]" captionTargetBox="[301,1339,1196,1872]" captionTargetId="figure-139@3.[301,883,1196,1872]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 4-5. Parahyliota balli Thomas, new species, female allotype. 4) Dorsal habitus. 5) Head and pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5405017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5405017/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Fig. 4-5</figureCitation>
) with same data as holotype, deposited in 
<collectionCode box="[1068,1157,261,285]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34871" name="Smithsonian Institution, National Museum of Natural History" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" type="Museum">USNM</collectionCode>
. Similar to male, differing as follows: Length, 
<quantity box="[469,562,293,317]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.4" pageId="5" pageNumber="4" unit="mm" value="6.4">6.4 mm</quantity>
. Head, 1.8x wider than long; pronotum, 1.3x wider than long; elytra, 2.1x longer than combined width; color castaneous; punctation and pubescence as in male; mandibles without dorsal tooth and frons without blunt tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[768,838,357,381]" captionStart="Figure 4-5" captionStartId="3.[193,277,1901,1923]" captionTargetBox="[301,1339,1196,1872]" captionTargetId="figure-139@3.[301,883,1196,1872]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figure 4-5. Parahyliota balli Thomas, new species, female allotype. 4) Dorsal habitus. 5) Head and pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5405017" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5405017/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="4">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); antennae about as long as body, scape attaining middle of pronotum; ratios of antennomere lengths: 5.0:1.0:2.0:2.3:2.3:2.3:2.0:2.0:1.6:2.0.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
